Semillar vs. the prosecutor's office: the cassation of the former deputy mayor of Tartu will be considered on August 4
This means that the decision on it is likely to be made in early September.
The courts of the first two instances refused to consider Semilarski’s claim, but in April his case appeal was accepted by the State Court.
On December 12, 2019, the Tartu Administrative Court returned the complaint to the applicant, as its permission does not fall within his jurisdiction of the administrative court.
The court's decision stated that the complaint contained a claim for compensation for damages caused during criminal proceedings.
“The prosecutor’s office and the exit court should regulate such matters,” ERR’s Tartu court press secretary Anette Kreitsmann told reporters.
According to her, Valvo Semilarski appealed this decision in the district court, which did not change the court’s decision of first instance on 5 February.
Now the judge will have to say his word.
According to Semilarski’s lawyer, Oliver Nyaes’s jury, his client has been suspected of robbery for about two years.
He now demands that the prosecutor’s office reject false allegations at his address and reimburse him for moral damages.
The reason for the complaint to the court was the statements of the Prosecutor for Special Cases of the Leuna County Prosecutor's Office Margus Gross, made by him in October 2017, when Semilarski along with another at the time of the detention of the deputy mayor of Tartu Artem Suvorov was detained on suspicion.
“Remember that when I was arrested, the security police and the prosecutor’s office immediately organized a press conference and informed the entire Republic of Estonia that the leaders of the Tartu – one of the most influential authorities of the local authorities – are being sold.
These airborne public suspicions have been accompanying me for about two years.
And now that these allegations and suspicions have turned out to be false, the prosecutor’s office doesn’t want to say anything about it,” Semilarski commented in early August 2019.
According to Oliver Nias, at a press conference, the prosecutor went beyond the legal framework in which the prosecutor's office is to act.
“Affirmation of bribes and scams turned out to be false, but that’s not the only problem here.
The European Court of Human Rights, for example, has repeatedly stressed in its rulings on Russia and Lithuania that at the stage of the investigation the representatives of the state should be cautious when choosing words so that the suspects would not be represented as criminals before the verdict.
The prosecutor’s office is also bound by the presumption of innocence, which, unfortunately, has not been observed in this case against Valvo Semilarski,” Nias said.
"The public perception of Semilarski as a serious offender and a predator in circumstances where the facts underlying the suspicion of pretense are still being clarified is unacceptable, which contradicts the presumption of innocence," he said.
According to rus.err.ee, the former deputy mayor Tartu Valvo Semilarski will not be brought to trial on charges of bribery - the criminal case initiated against him was partially closed in July.
At the same time, the former official is tried on charges of deliberate violation of anti-corruption legislation when conducting transactions of particularly large size.
According to the indictment, between 2015 and 2017, the former deputy mayor of Tartu participated more than thirty times in meetings of the city council in making decisions related to the companies operating in Tartu, with the owners or managers of which Semilarski actively communicated in person.
According to Gross, in all these cases Semilarski had personal interests, and therefore he had to refrain from participating in decision-making.
Earlier, as rus.err.ee wrote, the prosecutor’s office has alleged Semillarsky to have received a bribe and violated anti-corruption legislation when conducting transactions of particularly large sizes.
This happened in October 2016, when he was arrested together with another deputy mayor Artem Suvorov (Central Party).
