How the CB’s decision to lower the key rate will affect the economy
The Bank of Russia is expected to lower the key rate again.
It fell by another 0.25 percentage point, to 4.25% of the annual – formally another historical minimum.
Considering the return of the short step of the rate reduction, as well as the tonality of the CB’s statements and updated forecasts on the Russian economy, the regulator looks at the economic outlook more optimistic than before.
This means that the current cycle of monetary policy mitigation may soon stop.
“We have continued to mitigate monetary policy, primarily given that the risk of inflation deviation remains down from 4% in 2021,” said Elvira Nabiullina, head of the Bank of Russia.
They are linked to a significant decline in economic activity, a decline in domestic and external demand.
The recovery of the economy, according to Nabiullina, will take more than a year and a half.
At the same time, she noted that after the removal of restrictions due to the pandemic, economic processes have revived: energy consumption, consumer and investment demand have been restored, construction and production of consumer goods have been expanded, the annual rate of reduction in freight traffic has been slowed.
According to the CB’s forecast, in 2020 the economy will decline to 4.5-5.5% (previously expected 4-6%), and the economic recovery growth in 2021 will be 3.5-4.5%, and in 2022 - 2.5-3.5%.
In addition, the Bank of Russia revised the annual oil price forecast to <0x24>38 and <0x24>40 per barrel of Urals in 2020 and 2021, respectively.
Earlier, the CB expected <0x24>27 and <0x24>35 per barrel.
Finally, the Bank of Russia’s inflation forecast for 2020 was 3.7-4.2% against the previously anticipated 3.8-4.8%.
The Bank of Russia’s view of the situation in the economy is becoming more optimistic, which brings us closer to the end of the cycle of mitigation, economists in Russia and the CIS “Renaissance Capital” Sophia Donetsk and Andrey Melashchenko believe.
Thus, the Bank of Russia has consistently lowered its key rate for more than a year, and since the beginning of last summer it has fallen by 3.5 percentage points.
And at the last meeting in June, the ECB lowered it immediately by one percentage point due to low inflation rates due to depressed demand and the need to stimulate the pandemic’s slowdown and associated economic constraints.
The chances of monetary policy adjustment remain (at the next meeting on 18 September and until the end of the year), but the limit is already close, according to chief analyst of Rosbank Evgeny Koshelev.
The aggregate of pro-inflation risks also indicates the closeness of the interest rate policy pause – disrupted supply chains, a possible cost increase due to epidemic prevention measures and a faster (as opposed to expectations) recovery in demand, he says.
In order to complete the Bank of Russia’s follow-up actions will require more attention to inflationary processes during the harvest season, as well as external volatility, increased against the background of geopolitical conflicts, says Koshelev.
Either way, a reduction in the key rate will lead to further lower rates for the most reliable lenders, as well as possibly on the mortgage, says senior analytic management economist Maxim Petronevich.
The rate correction will be less pronounced than the reduction of the key rate, he clarifies.
Interests on mortgages can fall by another 0.3-0.6 percentage point during the second half, mortgage rates can end the year in the range of 6.2-7%, does not exclude economist "BCS Primer" Anton Pokatovich.
The average stakes on investments, he said, will also fall – in the coming months they may fall to 4.2-4.5% (now barely above 4.5%).
They can also fall to 4% if the central bank lowers the key rate in the fall, says Pokatovich.
