The actor of the Russian series responded to accusations of "propaganda of LGBT and feminism"
The actor of the Russian series "Chiki", whose creators were accused of "propaganda of LGBT and feminism", responded to claims to the film.
The authors "understand the acuteness of the topics raised and did not want to offend anyone," American Stephen Thomas Oksner said in a conversation with the publication "The Elevation".
“I think it’s a story about the power and the general aspects of human life.
It has nothing to do with LGBT and feminism,” said the actor, who played the father of the boy who was dressed in women’s clothing.
He stressed that he is “proud of the work” and does not consider it propaganda.
At the same time, the American added, he is frightened by the reaction of some people to the plot line of the series: for example, there was a case when “a man in deep sweat shot the shooter and said that all this was not true.”
“Then there were a couple of cases when we met dissatisfied locals who didn’t understand what we were doing.
But we were open, so the people who came first with the claims started to help us,” he added.
The shooting happened in September 2019 in Kabardino-Balkariya: a drunk man attacked the car of a shooting group with a gun, after which he was detained by police.
